value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: SeO3(2-) + 3NADPH + 5H+ = H2Se + 3NADP+ + 3H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: 3'-phosphoadenylylselenate + NADPH => adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate + selenite + NADP+ + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + CH3SeOH => NADP+ + CH3SeH + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + CH3SeO2H => NADP+ + CH3SeOH + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: phospho-L-arginyl-[protein] +H2O = L-arginyl-[protein] + phosphate.
The removal of phosphate residues from peptidyl-N-phospho-arginine to form peptidyl-arginine.
A process which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a trans-Golgi network membrane.
The clustering together of unicellular organisms in suspension form aggregates.

The binding by a cell-adhesion protein on a cell surface to an adhesion molecule on another cell surface or an external substrate, to mediate adhesion of the cell to the external substrate or to another cell.
The binding by a cell-adhesion protein on the cell surface to an extracellular matrix component, to mediate adhesion of the cell to another cell.
Binding to a collagen fibril.
The binding by a cell-adhesion protein on the cell surface to an extracellular matrix component, to mediate adhesion of the cell to the extracellular matrix.

label.value: protein complex involved in cell-cell adhesion

value.value: Any protein complex that is capable of carrying out some part of the process of cell-cell adhesion.

label.value: protein complex involved in cell adhesion

value.value: Any protein complex that is capable of carrying out some part of the process of cell adhesion to the cell matrix or to another cell.

label.value: protein complex involved in cell-matrix adhesion

value.value: Any protein complex that is capable of carrying out some part of the process of cell-matrix adhesion.

label.value: laminin binding involved in cell-matrix adhesion

value.value: Any laminin protein binding that occurs as part of cell-matrix adhesion.

label.value: collagen binding involved in cell-matrix adhesion

value.value: Any collagen binding that occurs as part of cell-matrix adhesion.

label.value: integrin binding involved in cell-matrix adhesion

value.value: Any integrin binding that occurs as part of the process of cell-matrix adhesion.

label.value: cadherin binding involved in cell-cell adhesion

value.value: Any cadherin binding that occurs as part of the process of cell-cell adhesion.
A collagen trimer that forms networks.
A supramolecular assembly of fibrillar collagen complexes in the form of a long fiber (fibril) with transverse striations (bands).
A complex of collagen trimers such as a fibril or collagen network.
A supramolecular complex that consists of collagen triple helices associated to form a network.
A protein complex that consists of collagen triple helices associated to form a sheet-like network.
A supramolecular assembly of collagen trimers with a 'beads on a string'-like structure.
A specialised collagen fibril that functions as an anchor, binding to other collagen structures.
Binding to a peptidyl-proline 4-dioxygenase.
Any collagen timer that is part of a basement membrane.
An antiparallel dimer of two collagen VII trimers, one end of which is embedded in the lamina densa while the other end attaches to banded collagen fibrils in the dermis.
The process by which centromeres/kinetochores become localized to clusters.

definition.value: As inner kinetochores are an integral part of centromeres, we treat centromere and kinetochore clustering as the same process.

value.value: A protein complex that includes Mis16(Yippee family) and/or Mis18 (WD repeat) subunits that is involved in the deposition of centromere specific (CENP-A containing) nucleosomes at the centromere.
The process in which a monoatomic cation is transported across a membrane. Monatomic cations (also called simple cations) are positively charged ions consisting of exactly one atom.
The process in which a monoatomic anion is transported across a membrane. Monatomic anions (also called simple anions) are negatively charged ions consisting of exactly one atom.
The directed movement of some substance from outside of a cell into a cell. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

label.value: inorganic anion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of inorganic anions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: inorganic cation import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of inorganic cations from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The process in which an inorganic ion is transported across a membrane.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: The process in which an inorganic anion is transported across a membrane.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: A process in which an inorganic cation is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

label.value: G protein-coupled serotonin receptor signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled serotonin receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.
A protein complex that is capable of serotonin receptor activity.
A protein complex that is capable of G protein-coupled serotonin receptor activity.

The process by which a preexisting viral infection prevents a secondary infection with the same or a closely related virus. Typically some aspect of viral entry is inhibited, but post entry mechanisms have also been documented.

label.value: entry receptor-mediated virion attachment to host cell

value.value: The process by which a virion attaches to a host cell by binding to a receptor on the host cell surface that mediates/triggers viral entry by endocytosis/pinocytosis or by inducing fusion/penetration.

label.value: adhesion receptor-mediated virion attachment to host cell

value.value: The process by which a virion attaches to a host cell by binding to a receptor on the host cell surface that does not mediate or trigger entry into the host cell. This binding is typically reversible and enhances significantly infectivity by concentrating the virus in the vicinity of its entry receptors, or bringing it to an organ in which its target cells are located.

label.value: symbiont-mediated suppression of host CRISPR-cas system

value.value: A process by which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the CRISPR-cas system of its host. Bacteria and archaea use CRISPR-Cas adaptive immune systems to defend themselves from infection by bacteriophages (phages), and phages have various mechanisms to counter the CRISPR-cas system.

label.value: inhibition of host DNA replication by virus

value.value: Any process by which a virus inhibits DNA replication in its host cell. Some bacteriophages are known to do this, possibly as a way of increasing the pool of nucleotides available for virus replication.

label.value: extrinsic component of neuronal dense core vesicle membrane

value.value: The component of the neuronal dense core vesicle membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: modulation of host virulence by virus

value.value: A process by which a virus improves the virulence of its host for that host's respective host. Common in but not limited to bacteriophages; also occurs in phage-bearing bacteria infecting plants or animals for example. Mechanisms include the expression of factors that modulate a bacterial adhesion to a host cell, spread through host tissues, production of exotoxins or provide protection against host immune defenses.

Maturation of a virion after separation from the host cell. Not all viruses mature after separation. In those that do, maturation typically involves rearangement and/or cleavage of viral proteins, resulting in the virion becoming competent for reinfection.
